@duststorm_ask_why_fail
title: Ask why a protected reserve still throws dust
max-visits: 1

Me: If the reserve is so protected, why is it still throwing dust into the harbour?

Ranger Neral gives a tired smile.

Ranger Neral: Because protected is not the same as functioning.

Ranger Neral: Visitors see open space and call it wild. But on the transects I see more standing dead grass, wider bare spaces between plants, more capped ground after rain, and less new establishment every year.

Facilyn: The reserve is trapped in a story that sounds wise but fits the wrong climate.

Facilyn: In a humid environment, long rest can allow land to recover quickly. But the eastern flats are brittle. Rainfall is seasonal and unreliable, humidity is poorly distributed through the year, and old plant material breaks down slowly.

Ranger Neral: From a distance it can still photograph well. Up close it is a weakening grassland.

