@duststorm_ask_stems
title: Pick up one of the gray stems
max-visits: 1

Me: What am I actually looking at here?

You pick up one of the stems. It is so dry it weighs almost nothing. When you press it lightly between your fingers, it shatters and leaves pale fragments in your palm.

Facilyn: That is oxidised grassland.

Facilyn: In brittle country, dead grass often does not decay quickly from the bottom up the way people in humid regions expect. It stays upright, gray, and weathered. Sun, dry air, and time break it down chemically and physically from the top downward.

Ranger Neral: The brochures call it natural senescence. On the ground it behaves more like a warning.

Facilyn: Because much of the material remains standing instead of being returned to the soil surface, it does not protect the soil well enough. Growth points stay shaded. Plants weaken. Their centers die. Bare gaps widen.

Ranger Neral brushes the fragments off your hand into the ash.

Ranger Neral: And then the wind starts billing the harbour for our mistakes.

